Absolutely! If your keyboard auto-switched to Chinese input and you ended up with Chinese punctuation in your English text, you can **find and replace** all the problematic characters in one go using **Find and Replace** in most text editors or word processors like **Microsoft Word**, **Google Docs**, or even **Notepad**.

Here’s a quick list of **what to find** and **what to replace** with:

---

### 🔁 **Find and Replace List (Chinese to English Punctuation)**

| Find (Chinese) | Replace With (English) |
|----------------|------------------------|
| ，             | ,                      |
| 。             | .                      |
| ：             | :                      |
| ；             | ;                      |
| “             | "                      |
| ”             | "                      |
| （             | (                      |
| ）             | )                      |
| ——             | – or —                 |
| ……             | ...                    |
| ？             | ?                      |
| ！             | !                      |

---

### ✅ How to Do This in Google Docs or Microsoft Word:

1. **Ctrl + H** (Windows) or **Cmd + H** (Mac) to open **Find and Replace**.
2. In the **Find** box, paste one Chinese character at a time from the list above.
3. In the **Replace with** box, type the corresponding English character.
4. Click **Replace All**.
5. Repeat for each punctuation pair.

---

### 🧹 Bonus: Use a Text Cleaner Tool

If you want to clean it all at once, you can use a free online tool like:

- **[https://www.textfixer.com/tools/remove-punctuation.php](https://www.textfixer.com/tools/remove-punctuation.php)**  
  → This will strip out all non-English punctuation.

Or try this **JavaScript snippet** if you're comfortable pasting into a browser console:

```javascript
let text = "3BR 2BA Sunnyvale – 新厨房，后院，靠近学校和科技公司。";
let cleaned = text.replace(/[，。：；“”（）——…？！]/g, function(c) {
    switch(c) {
        case '，': return ',';
        case '。': return '.';
        case '：': return ':';
        case '；': return ';';
        case '“': return '"';
        case '”': return '"';
        case '（': return '(';
        case '）': return ')';
        case '——': return '--';
        case '……': return '...';
        case '？': return '?';
        case '！': return '!';
        default: return c;
    }
});
console.log(cleaned);
```

Just replace the sample text with your own.

